        <article class="sw-writeup" id="writeup-roman-church" hidden>
          <header class="sw-writeup-head">
            <p class="sw-writeup-kicker">The Foundation</p>
            <h3 class="sw-writeup-title">Roman Church</h3>
            <p class="sw-writeup-sub">From Mithras to Mass</p>
          </header>
          <div class="sw-writeup-body">
            <p>The Roman Empire never actually converted to the faith of Yahushua. It did the opposite. It took that faith, stripped it of its Hebrew roots, and poured it into the existing molds of Roman sun worship. What came out the other side was not Christianity. It was Babylon with a new paint job. Because this site has a full section dedicated to Catholicism, this page will focus on one thing only — how the Roman Church became the mother of every institutional priesthood that followed.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Absorption, Not the Conversion</h3>
                          <p>For the first three hundred years, followers of the Messiah were hunted, tortured, and killed by Rome. Then suddenly, in the year 312, the Emperor Constantine claimed to have a vision in the sky and flipped the entire empire. Overnight, the outlawed faith became the state religion. But Constantine did not repent. He did not get baptized until he was on his deathbed. He kept his title as Pontifex Maximus — chief priest of the pagan cults — and simply reassigned that title to the head of the new Christian empire. The popes still use that title today. It is literally pagan.</p>
                          <p>Under Constantine, the Roman Church did not replace the old gods. It repackaged them. The sun god Sol Invictus had his birthday on December 25. That became the birthday of the Messiah, even though Yahushua was almost certainly born during the Feast of Tabernacles in the fall. The day of the sun — Sunday — became the day of worship, replacing the seventh-day Sabbath commanded in Exodus 20. The halos that appeared behind the heads of Ra, Helios, Mithras, and Sol Invictus in pagan art began to appear behind the heads of Peter, Paul, and even the Messiah Himself in church art. The obelisk of the Egyptian sun god Ra, stolen from Heliopolis, still stands in the center of St. Peter's Square in Rome. The monstrance that Catholics use to display the communion wafer is a sunburst — a literal image of the sun god holding a disc of bread in his mouth.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Priesthood Problem</h3>
                          <p>The sun worship is bad enough. But the deeper poison is the priesthood itself. Rome teaches that you cannot come to Yahuah directly. You need a priest. You need to confess to a priest. You need a priest to turn bread into the body of the Messiah. You need a priest to baptize your baby. You need a priest to read you your last rites when you die. From cradle to grave, the Roman Catholic is told they need a professional middleman to access their own Creator.</p>
                          <p>This is exactly the structure of every pagan priesthood that ever existed. The Egyptians had priests to mediate with the sun. The Babylonians had priests to mediate with Baal. The Romans had priests to mediate with Jupiter. When Rome absorbed the faith of Yahushua, it kept the priesthood structure and simply changed the name on the letterhead. Scripture is clear in 1 Timothy 2:5 — "There is one Elohim, and one mediator between Elohim and men, the man the Messiah Yahushua." One. Not a priest. Not a bishop. Not a pope. One mediator, Yahushua, and no one else has the job.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Pope Problem</h3>
                          <p>The pope claims to be the Vicar of the Messiah on earth — meaning the stand-in. The word "vicar" is where we get "vicarious." The pope claims to stand in the place of Yahushua. But Yahushua already sent His Spirit to dwell in His people. He does not need a stand-in. The pope wears a fisherman's ring, claiming to be the successor of Peter, though there is no evidence Peter was ever in Rome as the first pope. Peter was the apostle to the circumcision, not to the Gentiles (Galatians 2:7-8). The whole claim is built on sand.</p>
                          <p>The pope also claims infallibility when he speaks officially on matters of faith and morals — a doctrine formally defined in 1870 at the First Vatican Council. Only Yahuah is infallible. A man who claims what belongs only to Yahuah is committing the same sin as the king of Tyre in Ezekiel 28 and as the man of sin in 2 Thessalonians 2, who "exalteth himself above all that is called Elohim, or that is worshipped; so that he as Elohim sitteth in the temple of Elohim, showing himself that he is Elohim."</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Mother of Harlots</h3>
                          <p>Revelation 17 describes a woman sitting on seven mountains, dressed in purple and scarlet, holding a golden cup full of abominations, drunk on the blood of the saints. Rome sits on seven hills — a fact Rome itself has always celebrated. The cardinals wear scarlet. The pope wears purple. The golden cup sits on the altar at every mass. The blood of the saints — the millions slaughtered during the Crusades, the Inquisition, the persecution of the true remnant who refused to bow to Rome — cries out from the ground.</p>
                          <p>The woman is called the Mother of Harlots. A mother has daughters. The daughters are every church system that walked out of Rome's house carrying her clothes, her calendar, her doctrines, and her priesthood structure. This includes every Protestant denomination that kept Sunday, Christmas, Easter, the trinity, infant baptism, and the clergy-laity divide. It includes the megachurches. It includes the NAR. It includes the false prophet networks. Every one of them is a daughter. Every one of them has the same mother.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Why This Page Exists</h3>
                          <p>The other five buttons on this page — False Prophets, NAR, Political Christianity, Megachurches, Protestantism — are not separate systems. They are all expressions of the same priesthood that was born in Rome. They wear different clothes. They use different words. Some of them would be offended to be compared to the Vatican. But they all do the same thing: they insert themselves between Yahuah and His people, they claim authority Scripture never gave them, and they feed off the flock instead of feeding the flock.</p>
                          <p>The call is the same for all of them — Revelation 18:4, "Come out of her, my people." Come out of Rome. Come out of her daughters. Come back to the Messiah, who is the only mediator, the only priest of the better covenant (Hebrews 8:1-2), and the only one worthy to stand between you and the Father.</p>
          </div>
          <button type="button" class="sw-writeup-close" data-close>&larr; Close this study</button>
        </article>

        <article class="sw-writeup" id="writeup-false-prophets" hidden>
          <header class="sw-writeup-head">
            <p class="sw-writeup-kicker">The Wolves</p>
            <h3 class="sw-writeup-title">False Prophets</h3>
            <p class="sw-writeup-sub">Wolves in Sheep's Clothing</p>
          </header>
          <div class="sw-writeup-body">
            <p>Yahushua warned about false prophets more than He warned about any other threat to His people. He did not warn about atheists. He did not warn about Roman soldiers. He warned about people who would come in dressed like sheep and carrying His name on their lips. In Matthew 7:15 He said, "Beware of false prophets, which come to you in sheep's clothing, but inwardly they are ravening wolves." In Matthew 24:11 He said they would multiply in the last days. In Matthew 24:24 He said they would be so convincing that, if possible, they would deceive even the elect. This is not a small warning. This is one of the most repeated warnings in the entire New Testament.</p>
                          <p>So where are they? They are everywhere. But the biggest concentration in the English-speaking world today sits on a single platform called Elijah Streams.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Elijah Streams Pipeline</h3>
                          <p>Elijah Streams is the video arm of the Elijah List, founded by a man named Steve Shultz. The Elijah List sends "prophetic words" to hundreds of thousands of subscribers by email. Elijah Streams broadcasts those same prophets on video, live, several days a week. They also run a show called "Prophets and Patriots" that mixes prophetic words with political commentary, pushing the Christian Nationalist message hand-in-hand with the false prophecy machine.</p>
                          <p>The platform functions as a clearinghouse. Anyone Steve Shultz decides to call a prophet gets an audience. He has no filter. He has no biblical test. He has openly admitted that he does not screen the words — he leaves it to the viewer to decide what is true. But Scripture does not leave it to the viewer. Scripture gives us a direct test.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Test That Ends the Debate</h3>
                          <p>Deuteronomy 18:20-22 gives Yahuah's own standard for identifying a false prophet. "But the prophet, which shall presume to speak a word in my name, which I have not commanded him to speak, or that shall speak in the name of other elohim, even that prophet shall die. And if thou say in thine heart, How shall we know the word which Yahuah hath not spoken? When a prophet speaketh in the name of Yahuah, if the thing follow not, nor come to pass, that is the thing which Yahuah hath not spoken, but the prophet hath spoken it presumptuously: thou shalt not be afraid of him."</p>
                          <p>The test is simple. If it does not come to pass, the prophet did not hear from Yahuah. Full stop. There is no second chance. There is no "the Lord changed His mind." There is no "my interpretation was off but the word was real." Under Torah, a false prophet was put to death. Under the grace of the Messiah, he is not stoned, but he is not to be listened to either. He is a wolf, and the sheep are told to run.</p>
                          <p>Jeremiah 23:16 adds, "Hearken not unto the words of the prophets that prophesy unto you: they make you vain: they speak a vision of their own heart, and not out of the mouth of Yahuah." And Ezekiel 13:3 — "Woe unto the foolish prophets, that follow their own spirit, and have seen nothing!"</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Regulars and Their Record</h3>
                          <p>Apply this test to the regulars on Elijah Streams and the whole house collapses.</p>
                          <p><strong>Kat Kerr</strong> is perhaps the most flamboyant of them all, with bright pink hair and stories of flying around heaven in golden chariots. She has prophesied repeatedly that Donald Trump is Yahuah's anointed, that he would be reinstated after the 2020 election, and that America would enter a great revival under his leadership. She has described visits to heaven that sound more like a child's fantasy than anything in Scripture — candy mountains, ice cream rooms, people riding motorcycles in the clouds. None of it lines up with the sober descriptions in Revelation or Ezekiel. She prophesied that Trump would be reinstated. He was not. By Deuteronomy 18, that settles it.</p>
                          <p><strong>Hank Kunneman</strong>, pastor of Lord of Hosts Church in Omaha, told his followers to "look to the skies of your 4th of July" in 2021 for signs of the restored order coming fast. The Fourth of July came and went. No restoration. He also prophesied a massive move of Yahuah leading up to that date. It did not happen. He is still on the air, still prophesying, still collecting offerings.</p>
                          <p><strong>Robin Bullock</strong>, pastor of Church International in Alabama, specializes in dramatic pronouncements about Trump, the election, and judgment on America's enemies. He claimed direct revelation that Trump was the true president and would be reinstated. He has prophesied over and over about timelines that did not materialize. Like the others, he never takes the test of Deuteronomy 18 seriously.</p>
                          <p><strong>Julie Green</strong> pumps out prophecies almost daily. She has predicted the deaths of specific public figures who are still alive, the sudden collapse of specific governments that are still standing, and the exposure of specific individuals on specific dates that have long passed without event. She thrives on an audience that never writes anything down.</p>
                          <p><strong>Amanda Grace</strong> mixes prophecy with constant political commentary. Her words are carefully vague enough to allow endless reinterpretation. When a specific word fails, it is quietly buried and replaced with three new words the following week.</p>
                          <p><strong>Johnny Enlow</strong> is one of the loudest promoters of the Seven Mountain Mandate, the core doctrine of the NAR that tells Christians to take over the seven "mountains" of society. His prophecies often center on Trump being installed as Yahuah's chosen man to retake these mountains.</p>
                          <p><strong>Manuel Johnson</strong> speaks of heavenly visits and "mysteries." His material mirrors Kat Kerr's style of fantasy revelation.</p>
                          <p><strong>Lance Wallnau</strong> straddles prophecy and political strategy. He coined the phrase "Trump is the modern Cyrus" and has built an entire business around that one idea. He is also a central figure in the NAR, which is covered in its own button.</p>
                          <p>Every name on this list has prophesied things that did not come to pass. Every one of them is still on the air. Every one of them is still collecting money. Every one of them should, by the standard of Scripture, be ignored completely.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Why People Believe Them Anyway</h3>
                          <p>If the evidence is this clear, why do so many believers follow them? Because itching ears crave what is sweet, not what is true. Paul warned Timothy that this would be the exact mark of the last days. "For the time will come when they will not endure sound doctrine; but after their own lusts shall they heap to themselves teachers, having itching ears; and they shall turn away their ears from the truth, and shall be turned unto fables" (2 Timothy 4:3-4).</p>
                          <p>People love these prophets because they say what people want to hear. Your side is winning. Your enemies are going down. Yahuah is about to make America great again. The stock market is about to explode. Your finances are about to break open. Every prophecy is a sugar pill. Nobody is ever told to repent, to keep Torah, to leave Babylon, to come out of Sunday worship, to stop eating unclean food, to honor the feasts of Yahuah. Nobody is ever told anything hard. The false prophet tells you what you want. The true prophet tells you what you need.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Pattern They All Share</h3>
                          <p>Notice what these prophets never say. They never call anyone to repent of Sunday worship. They never call out Christmas or Easter as pagan. They never mention the true names Yahuah and Yahushua. They never call out the trinity as unbiblical. They never tell the Church to come out of Babylon. They only tell the Church to cheer harder for Trump, give more money to the ministry, and wait for the next word. This is the signature of the false prophet. They serve the system. They do not disturb it. They are paid priests of a dying religion.</p>
                          <p>They also operate almost entirely inside the 501(c)(3) church system, the NAR network, or both. They are not lone voices in the wilderness. They are nodes in a carefully connected network, appearing on each other's shows, promoting each other's conferences, selling each other's books. Iron sharpens iron, Proverbs says. These iron together, but they sharpen nothing. They dull each other and call it fellowship.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Way Out</h3>
                          <p>The way out is simple. Turn them off. Unsubscribe. Stop giving money. Open your Bible and read it yourself. The Spirit of Yahuah that lives in every true believer does not need a middleman in pink hair or a cowboy hat to tell you what Yahuah is doing. "The anointing which ye have received of him abideth in you, and ye need not that any man teach you" (1 John 2:27). You already have the Teacher. Every false prophet is a distraction from that truth.</p>
                          <p>Revelation 22:18-19 closes the entire Bible with a warning to anyone who adds to or takes away from the words of the book. The false prophets of Elijah Streams and the networks around it do both every single week. They add their own words and call them Yahuah's. They take away the commandments of Yahuah and replace them with political talking points. Run from them. Do not give them your attention. Do not give them your money. Do not give them your ears.</p>
          </div>
          <button type="button" class="sw-writeup-close" data-close>&larr; Close this study</button>
        </article>

        <article class="sw-writeup" id="writeup-nar" hidden>
          <header class="sw-writeup-head">
            <p class="sw-writeup-kicker">The Network</p>
            <h3 class="sw-writeup-title">NAR</h3>
            <p class="sw-writeup-sub">The New Apostolic Reformation</p>
          </header>
          <div class="sw-writeup-body">
            <p>The New Apostolic Reformation is the most organized, most funded, and most dangerous expression of the modern priesthood on earth today. It is not a denomination. It is not a single church. It is a network — a web of self-appointed "apostles" and "prophets" who believe they have been given authority over regions, cities, and entire sectors of culture. They run conferences. They commission each other. They operate worship music empires. They feed the false prophet pipeline. They push political candidates. They practice signs and wonders that have nothing to do with the Spirit of Yahuah. And they are coming for every church, every home, and every believer who will let them in.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Where It Came From</h3>
                          <p>The NAR as a movement was named and organized by a man named C. Peter Wagner in the 1990s. Wagner taught at Fuller Theological Seminary, where he spent decades developing theories of "church growth" that drew heavily from marketing, sociology, and a spiritual warfare system he borrowed from missionaries he had worked with. In his later years, Wagner declared that Yahuah was restoring the "office of apostle" to the earth and that a new reformation was beginning. He called it "the most radical change in the way of doing church since the Protestant Reformation" — and for once he was telling the truth, though not in the way he intended.</p>
                          <p>Wagner organized what he called apostolic networks. He commissioned men and women as apostles, handing them authority over regions and spheres. He founded the International Coalition of Apostles, served as its first "Presiding Apostle," and built an entire hierarchy of titles, levels, and ranks. Scripture does not authorize any of it. Wagner died in 2016, but the network he built is bigger now than it has ever been.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Seven Mountain Mandate</h3>
                          <p>The heart of NAR theology is called the Seven Mountain Mandate. This teaching says Christians must take dominion over seven "mountains" of society — government, media, education, business, family, arts and entertainment, and religion — before the Messiah can return. According to this doctrine, Yahushua cannot come back until the church conquers the earth for Him. This is not the gospel. This is the opposite of the gospel.</p>
                          <p>The Messiah said in John 18:36, "My kingdom is not of this world: if my kingdom were of this world, then would my servants fight." He told His disciples they would be hated, persecuted, and killed — not that they would rule from seven mountains. The apostle Paul said in 2 Corinthians 10:4 that our weapons are "not carnal, but mighty through Elohim to the pulling down of strong holds." The NAR has flipped this into a political and cultural war machine. They do not pull down spiritual strongholds. They try to capture cultural ones.</p>
                          <p>This is dominionism, plain and simple. It teaches that the church will bring in the kingdom by taking over everything. Scripture teaches the opposite. The kingdom comes when the King Himself returns, not when His followers seize Hollywood or the White House.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Seeds of Sorcery</h3>
                          <p>NAR theology is soaked in practices that are flatly forbidden in Torah. Deuteronomy 18:9-12 lists the things Yahuah calls an abomination — divination, sorcery, casting spells, consulting familiar spirits, necromancy. The NAR does all of them and calls them gifts.</p>
                          <p>"Prophetic activation" is divination dressed in church clothes. They teach people to close their eyes, feel the presence, and speak out whatever comes into their mind as a word from Yahuah. This is exactly what pagan diviners do. Real biblical prophecy is not a technique. It is a sovereign act of Yahuah speaking to a chosen vessel.</p>
                          <p>"Spiritual warfare" in the NAR style often includes things like "territorial spirit" mapping, where people are sent to "bind demons" over cities or countries. The Bible never commands this kind of practice. Michael the archangel himself would not dare to bring a railing accusation against the devil (Jude 9), but NAR teachers walk around shouting at principalities like they are scolding a dog.</p>
                          <p>"Grave soaking" is necromancy. Bethel members have been filmed lying on the graves of dead revivalists like William Branham — a known false prophet with heretical teachings — trying to soak up their "anointing." Deuteronomy 18:11 forbids anyone who consults or communicates with the dead. The Bible calls it sorcery. Bethel calls it impartation.</p>
                          <p>"Fire tunnels" involve people walking between two lines of NAR leaders laying hands on them to transfer a spiritual force. The manifestations that follow — uncontrollable laughter, barking, shaking, falling, speaking in tongues of unknown spirits — are nearly identical to the Kundalini awakenings of Hindu yoga and the ecstatic trances of ancient pagan cults. This is not the Spirit of Yahuah. This is another spirit. Paul warned in 2 Corinthians 11:4 about people preaching "another Yahushua" and receiving "another spirit." That is the NAR.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Key Figures</h3>
                          <p>Knowing the names helps identify when the NAR is in the room, even when it doesn't say its name.</p>
                          <p><strong>Bill Johnson</strong> leads Bethel Church in Redding, California. Bethel is the single largest producer and exporter of NAR doctrine in the world. Bethel Music and Jesus Culture — their music labels — put NAR theology into songs that now dominate Sunday morning worship in non-NAR churches that have no idea where the lyrics came from. If you sing Bethel or Jesus Culture songs in your church, you are singing NAR prayers over your congregation.</p>
                          <p><strong>Mike Bickle</strong> founded the International House of Prayer in Kansas City (IHOPKC). For decades he was treated as one of the most holy men in the charismatic world. In 2023, multiple women came forward with credible allegations of decades of sexual abuse and manipulation. IHOPKC split. Bickle was forced out. The rot at the top of a "prayer movement" exposed the rot in its entire theology.</p>
                          <p><strong>Lou Engle</strong> is famous for the massive "TheCall" stadium prayer events where young people are whipped into an emotional and spiritual frenzy. His events blur the line between prayer and political activism, often tied directly to specific candidates and issues.</p>
                          <p><strong>Cindy Jacobs</strong> is one of the self-declared "generals" of the prophetic movement, often on Elijah Streams and other platforms. She has prophesied for decades with an extensive record of things that did not come to pass.</p>
                          <p><strong>Dutch Sheets</strong> led a 50-state tour networking NAR leaders and pushing his "Appeal to Heaven" message tied directly to Christian Nationalist politics.</p>
                          <p><strong>Lance Wallnau</strong> is both a Seven Mountain Mandate founder and the man who popularized the "Trump is modern Cyrus" teaching. He ties political activism, prophecy, and dominionism into a single package.</p>
                          <p><strong>Rick Joyner</strong> leads MorningStar Ministries and has been in the NAR for decades.</p>
                          <p><strong>Che Ahn</strong> of Harvest International Ministry is one of Wagner's original appointed apostles.</p>
                          <p><strong>Brian Simmons</strong> authored something called The Passion Translation, a rewritten Bible that changes verses to support NAR theology. It is not a translation. It is a rewrite. Any church using The Passion Translation is teaching from a corrupted text.</p>
                          <p><strong>Todd Bentley</strong> was commissioned as an NAR evangelist by C. Peter Wagner himself in a televised ceremony in 2008. Within weeks, Bentley left his wife, began an affair with an intern, and the "Florida Outpouring" he had been leading collapsed. The apostles who commissioned him were publicly exposed as unable to recognize the true character of the man they had endorsed. None of them lost their titles over it. The machine rolled on.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Real Power Behind the Titles</h3>
                          <p>The NAR is held together by one thing — the claim that these men and women hold apostolic authority. If the authority claim is true, you must submit. If it is false, the whole thing falls apart. So what does Scripture actually say?</p>
                          <p>Ephesians 2:20 says the assembly is "built upon the foundation of the apostles and prophets, Yahushua the Messiah himself being the chief corner stone." A foundation is laid once. You do not re-pour the foundation of a building every generation. The apostles were the foundation. The Messiah is the cornerstone. That part of the structure is finished.</p>
                          <p>Acts 1:21-22 gives the actual qualification for an apostle. When the eleven replaced Judas, they said the replacement had to be someone "which have companied with us all the time that the Master Yahushua went in and out among us, beginning from the baptism of John, unto that same day that he was taken up from us." No one alive today qualifies. No one has walked with the resurrected Messiah in the flesh. The office is closed.</p>
                          <p>Paul calls himself the last apostle in 1 Corinthians 15:8 — "last of all he was seen of me also, as of one born out of due time." Last of all. Not "first of many to come later." The apostolic office, in the biblical sense, ended with Paul.</p>
                          <p>The NAR's claim to the office is a fraud. And if the claim is a fraud, the submission they demand is also a fraud. No one owes them any obedience, any loyalty, or any money.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Hierarchy the Messiah Forbade</h3>
                          <p>The NAR builds ranks — apostles over prophets, prophets over pastors, pastors over sheep. Wagner had levels and titles and commissioning ceremonies. It is as structured as the Vatican and just as unbiblical.</p>
                          <p>Yahushua addressed this directly in Matthew 23:8-11. "But be not ye called Rabbi: for one is your Master, even the Messiah; and all ye are brethren. And call no man your father upon the earth: for one is your Father, which is in heaven. Neither be ye called masters: for one is your Master, even the Messiah. But he that is greatest among you shall be your servant."</p>
                          <p>You are all brothers. One Master. One Father. One greatness, and that greatness is service, not rank. The NAR took a pen to this passage and crossed it out. Apostle, prophet, general, father, master — the very titles the Messiah forbade are now stitched into every NAR business card.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Political Partnership</h3>
                          <p>The NAR married politics in the most public way during the Trump era. Dutch Sheets, Lance Wallnau, Cindy Jacobs, Lou Engle, and many others openly campaigned, prophesied, and laid hands on political candidates. The network became indistinguishable from a political action committee. They brought their dominionism, their worship music, and their false prophecies into the White House. The "seven mountains" theology became a political strategy.</p>
                          <p>This is the exact trap the Messiah refused. When the crowd tried to make Him king by force, He withdrew. When Satan offered Him the kingdoms of the world, He said no. The NAR eagerly takes the deal the Messiah rejected. Whatever they are serving, it is not Him.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Way Out</h3>
                          <p>If you are in an NAR church, leave. If you sing NAR songs in your worship, stop. If you follow NAR prophets online, unfollow. If you read The Passion Translation, throw it away and get a real Bible. If your pastor is going to NAR conferences, confront him in love and if he will not repent, find another assembly. There is no neutral ground with this movement. It is not a variation of the faith. It is a different religion operating under the name of Yahushua — and it is one of the most organized counterfeit priesthoods Yahuah's people have faced since Rome first absorbed the sun worshipers of the empire.</p>
                          <p>2 Corinthians 11:13-15 says it plainly. "For such are false apostles, deceitful workers, transforming themselves into the apostles of the Messiah. And no marvel; for Satan himself is transformed into an angel of light. Therefore it is no great thing if his ministers also be transformed as the ministers of righteousness; whose end shall be according to their works."</p>
                          <p>False apostles. Not weak apostles. Not confused apostles. False ones. Paul used the same word for them that Yahushua used for the prophets in Matthew 7. Wolves. Sheep's clothing. Ravening underneath. The NAR wears the clothing better than anyone else on earth right now. That is what makes it so dangerous. And that is why the call from Revelation 18:4 applies to them as strongly as it ever applied to Rome itself — "Come out of her, my people, that ye be not partakers of her sins, and that ye receive not of her plagues."</p>
          </div>
          <button type="button" class="sw-writeup-close" data-close>&larr; Close this study</button>
        </article>

        <article class="sw-writeup" id="writeup-political-christianity" hidden>
          <header class="sw-writeup-head">
            <p class="sw-writeup-kicker">The Network</p>
            <h3 class="sw-writeup-title">Political Christianity</h3>
            <p class="sw-writeup-sub">When the Church Weds the State</p>
          </header>
          <div class="sw-writeup-body">
            <p>When the church climbs into bed with the government, the result is always the same: false worship dressed up as faith. Political Christianity is a broad movement that mixes the kingdom of Yahuah with the kingdoms of this world. It tries to build heaven on earth through votes, wars, and political power instead of through the gospel of the Messiah and obedience to Yahuah's Torah. Two main branches dominate this movement today — Christian Zionism and Christian Nationalism. They look different on the surface, but at the root they share the same idol: the nation-state.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Christian Zionism</h3>
                          <p>Christian Zionism teaches that the modern political State of Israel, founded in 1948, is the same as the Israel of the Bible. It claims that Yahuah's promises to Abraham pass automatically to anyone living in that country today, no matter what they believe about the Messiah. This idea was almost unknown in church history before the 1800s. It was created and pushed by an Irish preacher named John Nelson Darby, who invented a system called dispensationalism. Darby taught that Yahuah has two separate peoples — Israel and the Church — and two separate plans for them. This split was completely new. The early believers never taught such a thing.</p>
                          <p>Darby's ideas might have stayed small if not for a man named Cyrus Scofield. In 1909, Scofield published the Scofield Reference Bible, which printed Darby's notes right on the same pages as Scripture. Millions of people bought it. They began reading those man-made notes as if they were the Word itself. Within a few generations, most of the American Protestant world had swallowed dispensationalism whole. The funding behind Scofield's work has been traced to powerful Zionist lawyers and bankers in New York, including Samuel Untermyer. The Bible most American Christians grew up reading was, in many ways, a propaganda tool.</p>
                          <p>The truth Scripture actually teaches is very different. Real Israel is not defined by bloodline or borders. Paul writes in Romans 9:6 that "they are not all Israel, which are of Israel." In Galatians 3:29, he says, "And if ye be Messiah's, then are ye Abraham's seed, and heirs according to the promise." The true children of Abraham are those who walk in the faith of Abraham and follow the Messiah. The olive tree in Romans 11 has natural branches and grafted-in branches, but it is one tree, with one root, growing toward one Yahuah. Christian Zionism takes a knife and tries to cut that tree in half.</p>
                          <p>The fruit of this teaching has been terrible. Christian Zionists cheer on endless wars in the Middle East, believing they are helping fulfill prophecy. Pastors like John Hagee, who founded Christians United for Israel (CUFI), have spent decades pushing the United States into wars that benefit a foreign government while costing American lives and money. They send blank-check support to a nation-state regardless of what that nation-state does. They twist Genesis 12:3 — "I will bless them that bless thee" — into a slogan, when the verse was spoken to Abraham personally and finds its full meaning in the Messiah, the true Seed of Abraham (Galatians 3:16).</p>
                          <p>Many Christian Zionists also push hard for a third temple to be built in Jerusalem, complete with a renewed animal sacrifice system. But Yahushua the Messiah is the true Temple. He told the woman at the well that the day was coming when worship would no longer be tied to a mountain or a building (John 4:21-24). To rebuild a stone temple and offer animal blood again would be to deny that His sacrifice was final and complete. It would not be a fulfillment of prophecy. It would be an abomination.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Christian Nationalism</h3>
                          <p>The other branch of Political Christianity is Christian Nationalism. This movement teaches that America is a special Christian nation chosen by Yahuah, and that the way to bring His kingdom is by capturing the government, the courts, and the culture. Christian Nationalists wave the flag in the sanctuary, sing patriotic songs as if they were psalms, and treat the founding fathers like prophets. But the historical record tells a different story. Many of the founders were Deists, Freemasons, or Unitarians who denied core biblical beliefs. The country was not founded as a Christian nation. It was founded as a secular republic by men who, in many cases, belonged to lodges that worshiped at the same altars as ancient Babylon.</p>
                          <p>Christian Nationalism turns the Messiah into a tool for political power. It puts presidents on the level of King David and treats elections like holy wars. In recent years, many of its leaders have called Donald Trump a "modern Cyrus," anointed by Yahuah to save the country. Self-proclaimed prophets like Lance Wallnau, Paula White, and Kat Kerr have built entire ministries on this claim. They paint a man known for casinos, three marriages, and crude language as Yahuah's chosen vessel — and millions of Christians believe them. This is the same kind of thinking that led the Pharisees to reject Yahushua. They wanted a political king who would overthrow Rome, but He came preaching a kingdom that was "not of this world" (John 18:36). When His followers tried to make Him an earthly king by force, He withdrew (John 6:15). The Messiah refuses to be used as a political mascot — by either party.</p>
                          <p>The same trap catches believers on every side of politics. Some baptize the Republican Party. Others baptize the Democratic Party. Both are wrong. Both are forms of idolatry. The kingdom of Yahuah does not arrive on Air Force One, and it cannot be voted into office. Whenever the church marries the spirit of an age, she is widowed in the next.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Shared Root</h3>
                          <p>Both branches share the same root error: idolatry of the nation-state. They put their hope in flags, armies, votes, and parties instead of in the Messiah and obedience to Torah. They make alliances with the world to gain power, forgetting that "friendship with the world is enmity with Yahuah" (James 4:4). They confuse patriotism with godliness, as if loving a country were the same as loving its Creator.</p>
                          <p>There is also a hidden cost. To get a tax break, most political churches have signed up for what is called 501(c)(3) status. This makes them creations of the state, licensed by the government, and forbidden from speaking certain truths from the pulpit. The state becomes the head of the church, not the Messiah. Pastors trade the freedom to speak Yahuah's full word for a discount on their property taxes. Many do not even realize what they have given away. The Bride of the Messiah was never meant to ask Caesar for permission to exist.</p>
                          <p>This trap was set in 1954 by Lyndon B. Johnson, who pushed through what is now called the Johnson Amendment specifically to silence churches that opposed him politically. The deal was simple: take the tax exemption, but stay quiet about anything the government does not want preached. Most pastors took the deal without reading the fine print. Today, those same pastors will rage about every cultural issue from the stage but go silent on the things that actually matter — Sabbath, Torah, the names, the feasts, the trinity, and the real return of the Messiah. The muzzle is invisible, but it is tight.</p>
                          <p>Both branches also distort prophecy. They read the news instead of the Bible, looking for signs in headlines instead of in Scripture. They create endless date-setting predictions about wars, raptures, and antichrists. They turn Yahuah's Word into a political playbook instead of a call to repentance and obedience.</p>
                          <p>Dispensationalism is the engine that drives most of this. It chops Scripture into seven separate "ages" with different rules, different gospels, and different peoples. It teaches that the church will be raptured away before any tribulation, so believers do not need to prepare to stand. It teaches that the law was for one age and grace is for another. None of this is found in the early church. None of it was taught by the apostles. It was built in the 1800s and force-fed to the world through the Scofield Bible, Dallas Theological Seminary, and Hollywood-style novels like the Left Behind series. An entire generation of Christians is more familiar with Tim LaHaye than with the actual book of Revelation.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Way Out</h3>
                          <p>The way out is simple but costly. Believers must recognize that no earthly government — not Israel, not America, not any other — is the kingdom of Yahuah. That kingdom belongs to the Messiah, and it grows through repentance, obedience to Torah, and the gospel, not through politics. The early believers turned the world upside down without ever holding a single political office. They did it by living set-apart lives, walking in the commandments, and proclaiming Yahushua as the risen King.</p>
                          <p>A kingdom built on votes can be voted out. A kingdom built on the Messiah is forever. Come out of the political church. Stop pledging allegiance to flags and parties. Pledge allegiance to the King of kings, and walk in His Torah.</p>
          </div>
          <button type="button" class="sw-writeup-close" data-close>&larr; Close this study</button>
        </article>

        <article class="sw-writeup" id="writeup-megachurches" hidden>
          <header class="sw-writeup-head">
            <p class="sw-writeup-kicker">The Wolves</p>
            <h3 class="sw-writeup-title">Megachurches</h3>
            <p class="sw-writeup-sub">The Laodicean Stage</p>
          </header>
          <div class="sw-writeup-body">
            <p>The megachurch is the modern shopping mall of religion. Bright lights, smoke machines, rock concerts, coffee bars, bookstores, and a pastor in skinny jeans preaching a feel-good message that never mentions sin, repentance, or Yahuah's law. Tens of thousands of people pour through the doors every weekend, drop money into buckets, listen to a 25-minute pep talk, and go home thinking they have worshiped the Creator of the universe. They have not. They have been entertained.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Where It Came From</h3>
                          <p>Megachurches did not appear out of nowhere. They grew out of a movement called the Word of Faith, also known as the prosperity gospel. The roots go back to a man named E.W. Kenyon in the early 1900s. Kenyon mixed Bible verses with ideas from a movement called New Thought, which was a kind of mind-power religion teaching that your words can create your reality. Kenyon's teachings were picked up by Kenneth Hagin, who became known as the "father of the Word of Faith movement." From Hagin came Kenneth Copeland, Creflo Dollar, Joyce Meyer, Joel Osteen, T.D. Jakes, and many others. They all teach versions of the same lie: that Yahuah's main goal for your life is to make you healthy, wealthy, and happy, and that you can force His hand by speaking the right words and giving the right amount of money.</p>
                          <p>This is not the gospel of Yahushua the Messiah. It is sorcery dressed in a suit. The Bible calls it covetousness, which is idolatry (Colossians 3:5). The Messiah said, "Ye cannot serve Yahuah and mammon" (Matthew 6:24). Yet the entire prosperity movement is built on serving mammon while pretending to serve Yahuah. They teach that you must "sow a seed" — meaning send them money — to receive a "harvest" of blessing. This is religious gambling. It preys on the poor, the sick, and the desperate, who give what little they have hoping to receive a miracle, while the preacher buys another mansion or another private jet.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Lifestyles Tell the Story</h3>
                          <p>Look at the lifestyles. Kenneth Copeland owns multiple jets and his own private airport. He famously said he could not fly commercial because he would have to ride in a "tube full of demons." Joel Osteen lives in a multi-million dollar mansion in Houston. Creflo Dollar once asked his followers to buy him a $65 million Gulfstream jet. Joyce Meyer's ministry has been investigated for lavish spending on private travel and luxury items. These are not shepherds. They are wolves in soft clothing, fleecing the flock while the flock claps and shouts amen.</p>
                          <p>Compare this to the Messiah, who had nowhere to lay His head (Matthew 8:20), or to Paul, who worked as a tentmaker so he would not be a burden on anyone (1 Thessalonians 2:9). Compare it to the prophets, who were often poor, hated, and killed. The biblical pattern is the opposite of the megachurch. True servants of Yahuah are usually rejected by the world, not celebrated by it.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Doctrine Is Twisted</h3>
                          <p>The teaching itself is twisted at every level. Word of Faith preachers teach that human beings are "little gods." This is the exact lie the serpent told Eve in the garden — "ye shall be as gods" (Genesis 3:5). They teach that Yahushua had to be born again in hell, which is heresy. They teach that faith is a spiritual force that even Yahuah Himself uses, putting their idea of "faith" above Yahuah Himself. They teach that sickness and poverty are always the result of a lack of faith, which means they blame the suffering for their own suffering. None of this is found in Scripture.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Megachurch Model Itself Is Broken</h3>
                          <p>Beyond the prosperity movement, the megachurch model itself is a problem. The Bible describes a body, not a business. It describes elders shepherding small flocks, not CEOs running corporations. In Acts, believers met house to house, broke bread together, and knew each other personally (Acts 2:46). The megachurch turns this on its head. Members become anonymous spectators. Worship becomes a stage performance. The pastor becomes a celebrity who is unreachable. Discipleship becomes impossible because no one knows anyone.</p>
                          <p>Hillsong is a perfect example. Founded in Australia, it grew into a global brand with churches, music labels, conferences, and merchandise. For years it was the model that every aspiring megachurch tried to copy. Then the scandals came out — leaders stealing money, covering up sexual abuse, living double lives. The same pattern has played out at Mars Hill under Mark Driscoll, at Hillsong under Brian Houston and Carl Lentz, at Elevation under Steven Furtick, and at countless others. When you build the church on a celebrity pastor instead of on the Messiah, the whole thing collapses when that celebrity falls.</p>
                          <p>The seeker-sensitive movement, started by Bill Hybels at Willow Creek in the 1970s, is the blueprint behind the modern megachurch. The idea was to design church services to attract unbelievers — soft music, comfortable seats, no offensive talk of sin or hell, short sermons full of life tips. After decades of building this model, Willow Creek itself eventually admitted in their own internal study that it had failed to produce mature followers of the Messiah. Hybels was later removed from his position over allegations of sexual misconduct. The model produced consumers, not disciples. But by then, every other megachurch had already copied it.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Bethel and the Occult Wing</h3>
                          <p>Bethel Church in Redding, California deserves special mention. It is one of the most popular megachurches in the world today, and it teaches outright occultism. Bethel members practice "grave soaking," lying on the graves of dead preachers to absorb their "anointing." This is necromancy, which Torah forbids in Deuteronomy 18:11. They teach "fire tunnels" where people pass through lines of others laying hands on them to receive "impartation." They produce "glory clouds" that turn out to be glitter blown from the rafters. Bethel's worship music — through Bethel Music and Jesus Culture — fills churches around the world, spreading their false spirit to millions of unsuspecting believers who have no idea they are singing songs from a house of sorcery.</p>
                          <p>The same problem applies to Hillsong music and Elevation Worship. Together, these three networks — Bethel, Hillsong, and Elevation — produce most of the worship songs sung in modern churches every weekend. Even small Baptist and Pentecostal congregations who would never set foot in those megachurches sing their songs every Sunday. The doctrine carried inside those lyrics goes wherever the songs go. This is how a false spirit travels into thousands of churches that think they are safe. You cannot eat from a poisoned well and expect clean water.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Tithing Scam</h3>
                          <p>The financial system of the megachurch is built on a misuse of tithing. The Bible commands tithing in the Torah, but it has nothing to do with giving cash to a pastor. Tithes were agricultural — grain, wine, oil, and livestock — and they went to the Levites who served at the temple, to the poor, the widow, the orphan, and the stranger (Deuteronomy 14:22-29, 26:12). Every third year, the entire tithe stayed in the local town to feed those in need. There is no Levitical priesthood today. There is no temple in Jerusalem. The megachurch pastor is not a Levite. To demand 10% of your income as a "tithe" and use it to pay your salary, build your stadium, and fly your jet is theft committed in Yahuah's name.</p>
                          <p>Most prosperity preachers also misuse Malachi 3:8-10 — the verse about robbing Yahuah — to scare their congregations into giving. They never tell you that the rebuke in Malachi was aimed at the priests, not the people, and that the tithe being withheld was food meant for the poor and the Levite. Today's preachers have flipped the verse upside down. They aim it at the people instead of themselves, and they pocket the money instead of feeding the hungry. The very passage they use to demand your money condemns them.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Messages That Don't Save</h3>
                          <p>The messages from megachurch pulpits are designed to never offend. Joel Osteen is famous for not preaching about sin, hell, or the cross. He is a motivational speaker with a Bible prop. T.D. Jakes preaches a message of "destiny" and "purpose" without ever calling people to repent. The Messiah began His ministry with the word "Repent" (Matthew 4:17). Megachurch preachers begin theirs with "You are amazing." These are two different gospels, and one of them is no gospel at all.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Laodicea in High Definition</h3>
                          <p>Revelation 3:14-22 describes the Laodicean church — rich, increased with goods, in need of nothing, and yet wretched, miserable, poor, blind, and naked. The Messiah stands outside that church knocking at the door. This is the megachurch. It looks successful. The numbers are huge. The buildings are beautiful. The bands are tight. But the Messiah is not inside. He is outside, knocking, asking individuals — not the institution — to open the door and let Him in.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Way Out</h3>
                          <p>The way out is to come down from the bleachers and into a real assembly. Find or form a small group of believers who actually walk in Torah, who actually know each other, who actually obey the Messiah. Stop sending your money to celebrity preachers. Stop being entertained on the day Yahuah set apart for rest. The Father is not interested in your stadium. He is interested in your obedience.</p>
          </div>
          <button type="button" class="sw-writeup-close" data-close>&larr; Close this study</button>
        </article>

        <article class="sw-writeup" id="writeup-protestantism" hidden>
          <header class="sw-writeup-head">
            <p class="sw-writeup-kicker">The Foundation</p>
            <h3 class="sw-writeup-title">Protestantism</h3>
            <p class="sw-writeup-sub">The Half-Finished Reformation</p>
          </header>
          <div class="sw-writeup-body">
            <p>When Martin Luther nailed his Ninety-Five Theses to the door of the Wittenberg church in 1517, he sparked what is called the Protestant Reformation. Luther saw real corruption in the Catholic Church — the selling of indulgences, the worship of relics, the obvious greed of the Pope — and he protested. So did Calvin, Zwingli, and many others who came after him. They broke away from Rome and started new churches. We call those churches Protestant because they protested.</p>
                          <p>But the Reformation was not finished. It only went halfway. The Reformers walked out of Rome's house carrying a suitcase full of Rome's clothing. They threw out some of her doctrines but kept many others. They protested her authority but adopted her practices. Today, more than 30,000 Protestant denominations exist around the world, all claiming to follow Scripture alone, and yet almost every one of them still wears Catholic clothes. To leave Babylon completely, you have to know what she handed to her daughters.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Sun Day</h3>
                          <p>Start with the day of worship. The fourth commandment in Exodus 20:8-11 says, "Remember the Sabbath day, to keep it holy." The Sabbath is the seventh day of the week — what we now call Saturday. Yahuah set it apart at creation, before there was a Jew or a Gentile (Genesis 2:2-3). He commanded it forever. Yahushua kept it. The apostles kept it. The early believers kept it for hundreds of years.</p>
                          <p>So why does almost every Protestant church meet on Sunday? Because the Catholic Church changed it. In the year 321, the Roman Emperor Constantine — who was a worshiper of the sun god Sol Invictus — issued a law that all people in the empire should rest on "the venerable day of the Sun." Those are his exact words. The Catholic Church later confirmed this change at the Council of Laodicea in 364, even cursing those who continued to keep the seventh-day Sabbath. The Catholic Church openly admits they made this change. In their own catechisms, they boast that the change of the Sabbath is the mark of their authority over Scripture.</p>
                          <p>When the Reformers left Rome, they kept her sun day. Luther kept it. Calvin kept it. Wesley kept it. Today, almost every Baptist, Methodist, Presbyterian, Pentecostal, Lutheran, and non-denominational church in the world keeps it. They have replaced the commandment of Yahuah with the tradition of men, exactly as Yahushua warned about in Mark 7:7-9. Every Sunday morning, hundreds of millions of people who claim to follow the Messiah are unknowingly honoring the day dedicated to the sun.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Trinity</h3>
                          <p>The trinity is another piece of Catholic baggage that the Reformers carried out the door. The doctrine that Yahuah is "three persons in one being" was hammered out at the Council of Nicaea in 325, again under Constantine, and finalized at the Council of Constantinople in 381. The word "trinity" appears nowhere in Scripture. The phrase "three persons in one being" appears nowhere in Scripture. What you find in Scripture is one Yahuah, our Father, and one Lord, Yahushua the Messiah, the Son of Yahuah, who is the image of the invisible Father (Colossians 1:15) and the express image of His person (Hebrews 1:3). The Holy Spirit is the Spirit of Yahuah, the Father's own Spirit poured out, not a third separate person. Deuteronomy 6:4 declares, "Hear, O Israel: Yahuah our Elohim is one Yahuah." Yahushua quoted this as the greatest commandment (Mark 12:29). One. Not three.</p>
                          <p>The Reformers kept the trinity. They wrote it into their confessions. They burned and drowned anyone who denied it. John Calvin had Michael Servetus burned alive at the stake in Geneva in 1553 for rejecting the trinity. The Reformers protested some of Rome's doctrines but defended her crown jewel with the same violence Rome had used. The blood is on their hands, and the false doctrine is on their pulpits.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Pagan Holidays</h3>
                          <p>The pagan holidays came along too. Christmas on December 25 has nothing to do with the birth of Yahushua, who was almost certainly born during the Feast of Tabernacles in the fall. December 25 was the birthday of Sol Invictus, the unconquered sun, and fell during the Roman festival of Saturnalia. The Catholic Church baptized these pagan dates and called them Christian. The Reformers kept them. The Christmas tree itself is condemned by name in Jeremiah 10:2-4, which warns against cutting down a tree, decorating it with silver and gold, and setting it up in your house — "the customs of the people are vain."</p>
                          <p>Easter is even worse. The very name comes from Ishtar, the Babylonian goddess of fertility, sex, and war. Her symbols were eggs and rabbits — exactly what shows up on Easter morning. Yahushua did not rise on Easter. He rose during the Feast of Firstfruits, an appointed time of Yahuah commanded in Leviticus 23. The Reformers kept Easter. Most Protestant churches still do, never asking why they are decorating eggs and hunting rabbits in the name of the risen Messiah.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Replacement Theology</h3>
                          <p>Replacement theology is another Catholic invention the Protestants kept. This is the idea that the Church has replaced Israel, that Yahuah is done with His people, and that all the promises and commandments given to Israel now belong to a Gentile institution. This was developed by Catholic theologians like Augustine. It was used for centuries to justify the persecution of Jews and the rejection of Torah. The Reformers kept it. Even today, most Protestant pulpits teach that the law was for the Jews and grace is for the Christians, completely ignoring that Yahushua said, "Think not that I am come to destroy the law, or the prophets: I am not come to destroy, but to fulfil" (Matthew 5:17).</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Lawless Gospel</h3>
                          <p>This leads to the worst Protestant doctrine of all — antinomianism, the idea that the law was nailed to the cross. Protestants love the verse "you are not under the law but under grace" (Romans 6:14), but they read it backward. Paul is saying that grace is the means by which we are now able to keep the law, not an excuse to throw it away. He says in the very next verse, "What then? shall we sin because we are not under the law, but under grace? Yahuah forbid." Sin is the breaking of the law (1 John 3:4). If grace abolished the law, there would be no sin to be saved from. The Protestant gospel of "grace without obedience" is the gospel of the serpent — "ye shall not surely die" (Genesis 3:4).</p>
                          <p>True salvation comes through faith in the Messiah alone. Yahushua paid the price no one else could pay. But once a person has been saved, they are called to walk as He walked (1 John 2:6) — and He walked in perfect obedience to His Father's Torah. Salvation is the door. Torah is the path you walk after you go through the door. The Protestant church has bricked up the path and pretended there was nothing on the other side of the door.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">The Other Catholic Seeds</h3>
                          <p>Other Catholic seeds in Protestant soil include infant baptism, which most denominations still practice even though there is no biblical example of it. The pre-tribulation rapture is a 19th-century invention by John Nelson Darby that has nothing to do with Scripture. Once-saved-always-saved contradicts dozens of warnings in the New Testament about falling away (Hebrews 6:4-6, Hebrews 10:26-29, 2 Peter 2:20-22). The use of the title "Lord" in place of the Father's name Yahuah, and the Greek-Latin name "Jesus Christ" instead of the Hebrew name Yahushua Messiah, both came down through Rome. Each is a piece of Roman clothing that the Reformation forgot to take off.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Even the Sabbath Keepers Carry It</h3>
                          <p>Even those who keep the seventh-day Sabbath often kept the rest of Rome's package. The Seventh-day Adventist Church, for example, recognizes the Sabbath but holds tightly to the trinity, follows the writings of Ellen G. White as a "modern prophet," and in many cases still celebrates Christmas and Easter. Other Sabbath-keeping groups have similar issues. Keeping the right day is necessary, but it is not enough. To leave Babylon, you have to leave all of her — not just the calendar.</p>
                          <p>A church can meet on the seventh day and still be drinking from the harlot's cup if they have kept her doctrines. The day is necessary but not sufficient. The full call is to come out of her sins, her teachings, her holidays, her hierarchy, her trinity, her replacement theology, and her watered-down lawless gospel.</p>
                          <h3 class="sw-body-heading">Come Out of Her</h3>
                          <p>This is the call of Revelation 18:4 — "Come out of her, my people, that ye be not partakers of her sins, and that ye receive not of her plagues." Yahuah is not telling His people to come out of Catholicism only. He is telling them to come out of the entire Babylonian system, including her Protestant daughters. Sunday worship, the trinity, Christmas, Easter, replacement theology, antinomianism, the rapture, and the rest must all be left behind.</p>
                          <p>The good news is that there is a remnant. There are believers all over the world waking up, throwing off Rome's clothing, returning to the name of the Father Yahuah and the Son Yahushua, keeping the true Sabbath, walking in Torah, keeping the appointed times, and living as set-apart people. They are not perfect, but they are coming out. They are answering the call.</p>
                          <p>The question for every Protestant reading this is simple: will you stay in your grandmother's denomination because it feels familiar, or will you follow the Messiah even if it costs you everything? The Reformation was a beginning. It was never meant to be the end. It is time to finish what Luther started — and to finish it the right way, by going all the way back to the Scriptures, all the way back to Torah, and all the way back to the names and ways of the Father and His Son.</p>
          </div>
          <button type="button" class="sw-writeup-close" data-close>&larr; Close this study</button>
        </article>

      </div>
    </section>

